# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: quasi-newton-bfgs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] In numerical optimization, the **Broyden–Fletcher–Goldfarb–Shanno** (**BFGS**) **algorithm** is an iterative method for solving unconstrained nonlinear optimization problems.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] Like the related Davidon–Fletcher–Powell method, BFGS determines the descent direction by preconditioning the gradient with curvature information.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] It does so by gradually improving an approximation to the Hessian matrix of the loss function, obtained only from gradient evaluations (or approximate gradient evaluations) via a generalized secant method.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] Since the updates of the BFGS curvature matrix do not require matrix inversion, its computational complexity is only ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})$ , compared to ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ in Newton's method.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] Also in common use is L-BFGS, which is a limited-memory version of BFGS that is particularly suited to problems with very large numbers of variables (e.g., >1000).
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] The BFGS-B variant handles simple box constraints.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] The BFGS matrix also admits a compact representation, which makes it better suited for large constrained problems.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] The algorithm is named after Charles George Broyden, Roger Fletcher, Donald Goldfarb and David Shanno.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] It is an instance of a more general algorithm by John Greenstadt.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] The optimization problem is to minimize $f(\mathbf {x} )$ , where $\mathbf {x}$ is a vector in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , and f is a differentiable scalar function.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] There are no constraints on the values that $\mathbf {x}$ can take.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] The algorithm begins at an initial estimate $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ for the optimal value and proceeds iteratively to get a better estimate at each stage.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] where $B_{k}$ is an approximation to the Hessian matrix at $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ , which is updated iteratively at each stage, and $\nabla f(\mathbf {x} _{k})$ is the gradient of the function evaluated at **x***k*.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] The curvature condition $\mathbf {s} _{k}^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {y} _{k}>0$ should be satisfied for $B_{k+1}$ to be positive definite, which can be verified by pre-multiplying the secant equation with $\mathbf {s} _{k}^{\mathsf {T}}$ .
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] If the function is not strongly convex, then the condition has to be enforced explicitly e.g. by finding a point **x***k*+1 satisfying the Wolfe conditions, which entail the curvature condition, using line search.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] Both $U_{k}$ and $V_{k}$ are symmetric rank-one matrices, but their sum is a rank-two update matrix.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] BFGS and DFP updating matrix both differ from its predecessor by a rank-two matrix.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] Another simpler rank-one method is known as symmetric rank-one method, which does not guarantee the positive definiteness.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] In order to maintain the symmetry and positive definiteness of $B_{k+1}$ , the update form can be chosen as $B_{k+1}=B_{k}+\alpha \mathbf {u} \mathbf {u} ^{\mathsf {T}}+\beta \mathbf {v} \mathbf {v} ^{\mathsf {T}}$ .
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] Consider the following unconstrained optimization problem ${\begin{aligned}{\underset {\mathbf {x} \in \mathbb {R} ^{n}}{\text{minimize}}}\quad &f(\mathbf {x} ),\end{aligned}}$ where $f:\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R}$ is a nonlinear, twice-differentiable objective function.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] Perform a one-dimensional optimization (line search) to find an acceptable stepsize $\alpha _{k}$ in the direction found in the first step.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] If an exact line search is performed, then $\alpha _{k}=\arg \min _{\alpha }f(\mathbf {x} _{k}+\alpha \mathbf {p} _{k})$ .
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] In practice, an inexact line search usually suffices, with an acceptable $\alpha _{k}$ satisfying Wolfe conditions.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] In statistical estimation problems (such as maximum likelihood or Bayesian inference), credible intervals or confidence intervals for the solution can be estimated from the inverse of the final Hessian matrix .
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] However, these quantities are technically defined by the true Hessian matrix, and the BFGS approximation may not converge to the true Hessian matrix.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] The BFGS update formula heavily relies on the curvature $\mathbf {s} _{k}^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {y} _{k}$ being strictly positive and bounded away from zero.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] This condition is satisfied when we perform a line search with Wolfe conditions on a convex target.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] However, some real-life applications (like Sequential Quadratic Programming methods) routinely produce negative or nearly-zero curvatures.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] This can occur when optimizing a nonconvex target or when employing a trust-region approach instead of a line search.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] It is also possible to produce spurious values due to noise in the target.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/broyden-fletcher-goldfarb-shanno-algorithm] In such cases, one of the so-called damped BFGS updates can be used (see ) which modify $\mathbf {s} _{k}$ and/or $\mathbf {y} _{k}$ in order to obtain a more robust update.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/davidon-fletcher-powell-formula] The **Davidon–Fletcher–Powell formula** (or **DFP**; named after William C.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/davidon-fletcher-powell-formula] Powell) finds the solution to the secant equation that is closest to the current estimate and satisfies the curvature condition.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/davidon-fletcher-powell-formula] It was the first quasi-Newton method to generalize the secant method to a multidimensional problem.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/davidon-fletcher-powell-formula] This update maintains the symmetry and positive definiteness of the Hessian matrix.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/davidon-fletcher-powell-formula] and $B_{k}$ is a symmetric and positive-definite matrix.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/davidon-fletcher-powell-formula] The DFP formula is quite effective, but it was soon superseded by the Broyden–Fletcher–Goldfarb–Shanno formula, which is its dual (interchanging the roles of *y* and *s*).
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/davidon-fletcher-powell-formula] By unwinding the matrix recurrence for $B_{k}$ , the DFP formula can be expressed as a compact matrix representation.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/davidon-fletcher-powell-formula] The inverse compact representation can be found by applying the Sherman-Morrison-Woodbury inverse to $B_{k}$ .
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/davidon-fletcher-powell-formula] The compact representation is particularly useful for limited-memory and constrained problems.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] Due to its resulting linear memory requirement, the L-BFGS method is particularly well suited for optimization problems with many variables.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] Instead of the inverse Hessian **H***k*, L-BFGS maintains a history of the past *m* updates of the position **x** and gradient ∇*f*(**x**), where generally the history size *m* can be small (often $m<10$ ).
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] These updates are used to implicitly do operations requiring the **H***k*-vector product.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] The algorithm starts with an initial estimate of the optimal value, $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ , and proceeds iteratively to refine that estimate with a sequence of better estimates $\mathbf {x} _{1},\mathbf {x} _{2},\ldots$ .
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] The derivatives of the function $g_{k}:=\nabla f(\mathbf {x} _{k})$ are used as a key driver of the algorithm to identify the direction of steepest descent, and also to form an estimate of the Hessian matrix (second derivative) of $f(\mathbf {x} )$ .
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] L-BFGS shares many features with other quasi-Newton algorithms, but is very different in how the matrix-vector multiplication $d_{k}=-H_{k}g_{k}$ is carried out, where $d_{k}$ is the approximate Newton's direction, $g_{k}$ is the current gradient, and $H_{k}$ is the inverse of the Hessian matrix.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] There are multiple published approaches using a history of updates to form this direction vector.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] We take as given $x_{k}$ , the position at the k-th iteration, and $g_{k}\equiv \nabla f(x_{k})$ where f is the function being minimized, and all vectors are column vectors.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] We define $\rho _{k}={\frac {1}{y_{k}^{\top }s_{k}}}$ , and $H_{k}^{0}$ will be the 'initial' approximate of the inverse Hessian that our estimate at iteration k begins with.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] The value of $z_{k}$ is then our ascent direction.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] This formulation gives the search direction for the minimization problem, i.e., $z=-H_{k}g_{k}$ .
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] For maximization problems, one should thus take -z instead.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] Note that the initial approximate inverse Hessian $H_{k}^{0}$ is chosen as a diagonal matrix or even a multiple of the identity matrix since this is numerically efficient.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] The scaling of the initial matrix $\gamma _{k}$ ensures that the search direction is well scaled and therefore the unit step length is accepted in most iterations.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] A Wolfe line search is used to ensure that the curvature condition is satisfied and the BFGS updating is stable.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] Note that some software implementations use an Armijo backtracking line search, but cannot guarantee that the curvature condition $y_{k}^{\top }s_{k}>0$ will be satisfied by the chosen step since a step length greater than 1 may be needed to satisfy this condition.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] Some implementations address this by skipping the BFGS update when $y_{k}^{\top }s_{k}$ is negative or too close to zero, but this approach is not generally recommended since the updates may be skipped too often to allow the Hessian approximation $H_{k}$ to capture important curvature information.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] Some solvers employ so called damped (L)BFGS update which modifies quantities $s_{k}$ and $y_{k}$ in order to satisfy the curvature condition.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] The two-loop recursion formula is widely used by unconstrained optimizers due to its efficiency in multiplying by the inverse Hessian.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] However, it does not allow for the explicit formation of either the direct or inverse Hessian and is incompatible with non-box constraints.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] An alternative approach is the compact representation, which involves a low-rank representation for the direct and/or inverse Hessian.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] This represents the Hessian as a sum of a diagonal matrix and a low-rank update.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] Such a representation enables the use of L-BFGS in constrained settings, for example, as part of the SQP method.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] L-BFGS has been called "the algorithm of choice" for fitting log-linear (MaxEnt) models and conditional random fields with $\ell _{2}$ -regularization.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] Since BFGS (and hence L-BFGS) is designed to minimize smooth functions without constraints, the L-BFGS algorithm must be modified to handle functions that include non-differentiable components or constraints.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] A popular class of modifications are called active-set methods, based on the concept of the active set.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] The idea is that when restricted to a small neighborhood of the current iterate, the function and constraints can be simplified.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] The **L-BFGS-B** algorithm extends L-BFGS to handle simple box constraints (a.k.a. bound constraints) on variables; that is, constraints of the form *li* ≤ *xi* ≤ *ui* where li and ui are per-variable constant lower and upper bounds, respectively (for each xi, either or both bounds may be omitted).
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] The method works by identifying fixed and free variables at every step (using a simple gradient method), and then using the L-BFGS method on the free variables only to get higher accuracy, and then repeating the process.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] where g is a differentiable convex loss function.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] The method is an active-set type method: at each iterate, it estimates the sign of each component of the variable, and restricts the subsequent step to have the same sign.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] Once the sign is fixed, the non-differentiable $\|{\vec {x}}\|_{1}$ term becomes a smooth linear term which can be handled by L-BFGS.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] After an L-BFGS step, the method allows some variables to change sign, and repeats the process.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] Schraudolph *et al.* present an online approximation to both BFGS and L-BFGS.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] Similar to stochastic gradient descent, this can be used to reduce the computational complexity by evaluating the error function and gradient on a randomly drawn subset of the overall dataset in each iteration.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/limited-memory-bfgs] It has been shown that O-LBFGS has a global almost sure convergence while the online approximation of BFGS (O-BFGS) is not necessarily convergent.
