[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Newton's method requires the Jacobian matrix of all partial derivatives of a multivariate function when used to search for zeros or the Hessian matrix when used for finding extrema.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Quasi-Newton methods, on the other hand, can be used when the Jacobian matrices or Hessian matrices are unavailable or are impractical to compute at every iteration.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Some iterative methods that reduce to Newton's method, such as sequential quadratic programming, may also be considered quasi-Newton methods.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Newton's method to find zeroes of a function g of multiple variables is given by $x_{n+1}=x_{n}-[J_{g}(x_{n})]^{-1}g(x_{n})$ , where $[J_{g}(x_{n})]^{-1}$ is the right inverse of the Jacobian matrix $J_{g}(x_{n})$ of g evaluated for $x_{n}$ .
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Strictly speaking, any method that replaces the exact Jacobian $J_{g}(x_{n})$ with an approximation is a quasi-Newton method.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] For instance, the chord method (where $J_{g}(x_{n})$ is replaced by $J_{g}(x_{0})$ for all iterations) is a simple example.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] The methods given below for optimization refer to an important subclass of quasi-Newton methods, secant methods.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Using methods developed to find extrema in order to find zeroes is not always a good idea, as the majority of the methods used to find extrema require that the matrix that is used is symmetrical.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] While this holds in the context of the search for extrema, it rarely holds when searching for zeroes.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Broyden's "good" and "bad" methods are two methods commonly used to find extrema that can also be applied to find zeroes.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Other methods that can be used are the column-updating method, the inverse column-updating method, the quasi-Newton least squares method and the quasi-Newton inverse least squares method.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] More recently quasi-Newton methods have been applied to find the solution of multiple coupled systems of equations (e.g. fluid–structure interaction problems or interaction problems in physics).
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] They allow the solution to be found by solving each constituent system separately (which is simpler than the global system) in a cyclic, iterative fashion until the solution of the global system is found.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] The search for a minimum or maximum of a scalar-valued function is closely related to the search for the zeroes of the gradient of that function.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Therefore, quasi-Newton methods can be readily applied to find extrema of a function.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] In other words, if g is the gradient of f , then searching for the zeroes of the vector-valued function g corresponds to the search for the extrema of the scalar-valued function f ; the Jacobian of g now becomes the Hessian of f .
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] The main difference is that the Hessian matrix is a symmetric matrix, unlike the Jacobian when searching for zeroes.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Most quasi-Newton methods used in optimization exploit this symmetry.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] In optimization, **quasi-Newton methods** (a special case of **variable-metric methods**) are algorithms for finding local maxima and minima of functions.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Quasi-Newton methods for optimization are based on Newton's method to find the stationary points of a function, points where the gradient is 0.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Newton's method assumes that the function can be locally approximated as a quadratic in the region around the optimum, and uses the first and second derivatives to find the stationary point.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] In higher dimensions, Newton's method uses the gradient and the Hessian matrix of second derivatives of the function to be minimized.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] In quasi-Newton methods the Hessian matrix does not need to be computed.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] The Hessian is updated by analyzing successive gradient vectors instead.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Quasi-Newton methods are a generalization of the secant method to find the root of the first derivative for multidimensional problems.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] In multiple dimensions the secant equation is under-determined, and quasi-Newton methods differ in how they constrain the solution, typically by adding a simple low-rank update to the current estimate of the Hessian.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] The first quasi-Newton algorithm was proposed by William C.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Davidon, a physicist working at Argonne National Laboratory.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] He developed the first quasi-Newton algorithm in 1959: the DFP updating formula, which was later popularized by Fletcher and Powell in 1963, but is rarely used today.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] The most common quasi-Newton algorithms are currently the SR1 formula (for "symmetric rank-one"), the BHHH method, the widespread BFGS method (suggested independently by Broyden, Fletcher, Goldfarb, and Shanno, in 1970), and its low-memory extension L-BFGS.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] The Broyden's class is a linear combination of the DFP and BFGS methods.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] The SR1 formula does not guarantee the update matrix to maintain positive-definiteness and can be used for indefinite problems.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] The Broyden's method does not require the update matrix to be symmetric and is used to find the root of a general system of equations (rather than the gradient) by updating the Jacobian (rather than the Hessian).
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] One of the chief advantages of quasi-Newton methods over Newton's method is that the Hessian matrix (or, in the case of quasi-Newton methods, its approximation) B does not need to be inverted.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Newton's method, and its derivatives such as interior point methods, require the Hessian to be inverted, which is typically implemented by solving a system of linear equations and is often quite costly.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] In contrast, quasi-Newton methods usually generate an estimate of $B^{-1}$ directly.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] As in Newton's method, one uses a second-order approximation to find the minimum of a function $f(x)$ .
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] where ( $\nabla f$ ) is the gradient, and B an approximation to the Hessian matrix.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] which is called the *secant equation* (the Taylor series of the gradient itself).
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] In more than one dimension B is underdetermined.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Using n different secants would be enough to determine B , but is equivalent to computing a finite difference Hessian.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] In one dimension, solving for B and applying the Newton's step with the updated value is equivalent to the secant method.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] The various quasi-Newton methods differ in their choice of the solution to the secant equation (in one dimension, all the variants are equivalent).
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] An approximate initial value $B_{0}=\beta I$ is often sufficient to achieve rapid convergence, although there is no general strategy to choose $\beta$ .
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Note that $B_{0}$ should be positive-definite.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] is used to update the approximate Hessian $B_{k+1}$ , or directly its inverse $H_{k+1}=B_{k+1}^{-1}$ using the Sherman–Morrison formula.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Other methods are Pearson's method, McCormick's method, the Powell symmetric Broyden (PSB) method and Greenstadt's method.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] These recursive low-rank matrix updates can also represented as an initial matrix plus a low-rank correction.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] This is the Compact quasi-Newton representation, which is particularly effective for constrained and/or large problems.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] When f is a convex quadratic function with positive-definite Hessian B , one would expect the matrices $H_{k}$ generated by a quasi-Newton method to converge to the inverse Hessian $H=B^{-1}$ .
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] This is indeed the case for the class of quasi-Newton methods based on least-change updates.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Suggestions for further optimization of the solution behavior of quasi-Newton methods are also given.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] 1) The methods are quasi-Newton methods.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] 2) The matrices $H_{i}$ are positive definite for all iterations.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] 3) For all iterations $i\geq 0$ , we obtain solutions to the minimization problem.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] For exact beam minimization and quadratic objective functions, each of these methods also terminates at the minimum point after at most n iteration steps.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] In particular, the regular quasi-Newton methods have the good properties of both the extended Greenstadt class and the symmetric, extended Huang class with regard to convergence and stability.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] It can be assumed that all particularly powerful quasi-Newton methods are regular.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/quasi-newton-method] Implementations of quasi-Newton methods are available in many programming languages.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] In numerical analysis, the **secant method** is a root-finding algorithm that uses a succession of roots of secant lines to better approximate a root of a function *f*.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] The secant method can be thought of as a finite-difference approximation of Newton's method, so it is considered a quasi-Newton method.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] Historically, it is as an evolution of the method of false position, which predates Newton's method by over 3000 years.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] The secant method is an iterative numerical method for finding a zero of a function f.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] This is a nonlinear second-order recurrence that is well-defined given f and the two initial values *x*0 and *x*1.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] Ideally, the initial values should be chosen close to the desired zero.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] Starting with initial values *x*0 and *x*1, we construct a line through the points (*x*0, *f*(*x*0)) and (*x*1, *f*(*x*1)), as shown in the picture above.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] We then use this new value of x as *x*2 and repeat the process, using *x*1 and *x*2 instead of *x*0 and *x*1.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] The iterates $x_{n}$ of the secant method converge to a root of f if the initial values $x_{0}$ and $x_{1}$ are sufficiently close to the root and f is well-behaved.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] When f is twice continuously differentiable and the root in question is a simple root, i.e., it has multiplicity 1, the order of convergence is the golden ratio $\varphi =(1+{\sqrt {5}})/2\approx 1.618.$ This convergence is superlinear but subquadratic.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] If the initial values are not close enough to the root or f is not well-behaved, then there is no guarantee that the secant method converges at all.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] There is no general definition of "close enough", but the criterion for convergence has to do with how "wiggly" the function is on the interval between the initial values.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] For example, if f is differentiable on that interval and there is a point where $f'=0$ on the interval, then the algorithm may not converge.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] The secant method does not require or guarantee that the root remains bracketed by sequential iterates, like the bisection method does, and hence it does not always converge.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] The false position method (or *regula falsi*) uses the same formula as the secant method.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] However, it does not apply the formula on $x_{n-1}$ and $x_{n-2}$ , like the secant method, but on $x_{n-1}$ and on the last iterate $x_{k}$ such that $f(x_{k})$ and $f(x_{n-1})$ have a different sign.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] This means that the false position method always converges; however, only with a linear order of convergence.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] Bracketing with a super-linear order of convergence as the secant method can be attained with improvements to the false position method (see Regula falsi § Improvements in *regula falsi*) such as the ITP method or the Illinois method.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] The secant method can be interpreted as a method in which the derivative is replaced by an approximation and is thus a quasi-Newton method.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] If we compare Newton's method with the secant method, we see that Newton's method converges faster (order 2 against order the golden ratio *φ* ≈ 1.6).
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] However, Newton's method requires the evaluation of both f and its derivative $f'$ at every step, while the secant method only requires the evaluation of f .
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] Therefore, the secant method may sometimes be faster in practice.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] In higher dimensions, the full set of partial derivatives required for Newton's method, that is, the Jacobian matrix, may become much more expensive to calculate than the function itself.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] If, however, we consider parallel processing for the evaluation of the derivative or derivatives, Newton's method can be faster in clock time though still costing more computational operations overall.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] Broyden's method is a generalization of the secant method to more than one dimension.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] The following graph shows the function *f* in red and the last secant line in bold blue.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] In the graph, the *x* intercept of the secant line seems to be a good approximation of the root of *f*.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] Below, the secant method is implemented in the Python programming language.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] It is very important to have a good stopping criterion above, otherwise, due to limited numerical precision of floating point numbers, the algorithm can return inaccurate results if running for too many iterations.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/secant-method] For example, the loop above can stop when one of these is reached first: abs(x0 - x1) < tol, or abs(x0/x1-1) < tol, or abs(f(x1)) < tol.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/symmetric-rank-one] The **Symmetric Rank 1** (**SR1**) method is a quasi-Newton method to update the second derivative (Hessian) based on the derivatives (gradients) calculated at two points.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/symmetric-rank-one] It is a generalization to the secant method for a multidimensional problem.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/symmetric-rank-one] This update maintains the *symmetry* of the matrix but does *not* guarantee that the update be *positive definite*.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/symmetric-rank-one] The SR1 method has computational advantages for sparse or partially separable problems.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/symmetric-rank-one] The above secant-equation need not have a unique solution B .
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/symmetric-rank-one] One might wonder why positive-definiteness is not preserved — after all, a rank-1 update of the form $B_{k+1}=B_{k}+vv^{T}$ is positive-definite if $B_{k}$ is.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/symmetric-rank-one] The explanation is that the update might be of the form $B_{k+1}=B_{k}-vv^{T}$ instead because the denominator can be negative, and in that case there are no guarantees about positive-definiteness.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/symmetric-rank-one] The SR1 formula has been rediscovered a number of times.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/symmetric-rank-one] The SR1 update maintains a dense matrix, which can be prohibitive for large problems.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/symmetric-rank-one] Similar to the L-BFGS method also a limited-memory SR1 (L-SR1) algorithm exists.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/symmetric-rank-one] Instead of storing the full Hessian approximation, a L-SR1 method only stores the m most recent pairs $\{(s_{i},y_{i})\}_{i=k-m}^{k-1}$ , where $\Delta x_{i}:=s_{i}$ and m is an integer much smaller than the problem size ( $m\ll n$ ).
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/symmetric-rank-one] Since the update can be indefinite, the L-SR1 algorithm is suitable for a trust-region strategy.
[src:quasi-newton-bfgs/symmetric-rank-one] Because of the limited-memory matrix, the trust-region L-SR1 algorithm scales linearly with the problem size, just like L-BFGS.
